              <div>
                  <head>Arabic roots</head>
                  
                  <p xml:space="preserve">In order to facilitate cross-dialectal comparative search all word
        roots are have to be taken as being strictly etymological, i.e. they
        reflect the corresponding roots of Standard Arabic wherever
        possible. The source of reference is the Dictionary of Modern
        Written Arabic by Hans Wehr (English version edited by J. Milton
        Cowell, Wiesbaden: Harrassowitz, 1979). For words which have entered
        Arabic from other languages a (in many hypothetical) root consisting
        of the mere consonantal structure of the word in question is
        given.</p>
              </div>
              
              <div>
                  <head>Part-of-speech</head>
                  
                  <p xml:space="preserve">As for verbs a subcategory indicating the so-called verbal form is
        provided (using the traditional order labelled by Roman numerals
        from I to X, in case of quadriliteral roots Iq and IIq).</p>
                  
                  <p xml:space="preserve">In many cases a clear distinction between adjective and active or
        passive participle is not possible. If a given lemma is mainly used
        in an adjectival sense it is labelled as such but with an additional
        category that indicates the word is morphologically seen a
        participle.</p>
                  
                  <p xml:space="preserve">The gender of Arabic nouns is not noted unless it is contradictory
        to the rules of Arabic morphology (which is particularly the case
        with unmarked feminine nouns).</p>
              </div>
